“Our elections were delayed by the coronavirus pandemic but we are determined  to hold them in the next few weeks so that those elected into office can start organising basketball activities immediately since we are already behind schedule,” Kisoi, who will be hoping to succeed  Vitalis Gode as the new KBF secretary general, said.
Gode, who has served as a top KBF official for two decades, has already indicated he will not be defending his seat at the federation opting to concentrate on his role as Fiba referees supervisor.





According to Kisoi, branches, commissions and teams are required to send names of two delegates who will participate in the national polls by January 11.
All aspiring candidates for national office should have returned forms to the elections panel by January 15 ready ahead of January 23 polls.
The calendar of events also include the Africa Women’s Club Championships in March where Kenya teams Kenya Ports Authority and Equity Bank are expected to take part, the Anoca Youth games set for Cairo in April and men's Afrobasket final tour set for Rwanda in August. 
According to the calendar, the first leg of the National Classic Basketball league will tip off on February 6, after the pre-season tournament on January 31 at Nyayo National stadium in Nairobi.



